f Evangelical Cultures -- t16. Religious Switching and Knowledge among Adolescents in Singapore -- tIII. RELIGION IN THE MEDIA -- t17. Religious Reasons in a Secular Public Sphere: Debates in the Media about Homosexuality -- t18. The Internet and Religious Harmony in Singapore -- tIV. RELIGIOUS ORGANIZATIONS IN SOCIAL SERVICES -- t19. Muslim Organizations and Mosques as Social Service Providers -- t20. Hindu Temples in Charities and Social Services -- t21. Delivering Welfare Services in Singapore: A Strategic Partnership between Buddhism and the State -- t22. Saving the City through Good Works: Christian Involvement in Social Services -- tV. INTERFAITH ISSUES AND INTERACTION -- t23. Religious Diversity, Toleration and Interaction -- t24. Negotiating Christianity with Other Religions: The Views of Christian Clergymen in Singapore -- t25. The Inter-Religious Organization of Singapore -- t26. Interactions among Youth Leaders of Different Faiths: Realities from the Ground and Lessons Learnt -- t27. Building Bridges between Christians and Muslims: A Personal Journey -- t28. Conclusion: Some Remarks on Religious Diversity in Singapore -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReligious and ethno-religious issues are inherent in many multiethnic and multi-religious societies. Singapore society is no exception. It has long been multiethnic, multicultural and multi-religious, being at the crossroads of many major and minor civilizations, cultures and traditions, and its religious diversity continues to develop in the current contexts of growing religiosity, religious change and conflict often in the name of religion. Despite this background, there is lack of in-depth knowledge, nuanced understanding and regular dialogue about religions and the meanings of living in a multi-religious world. This volume covering major themes of Singapore's religious landscape, religion in schools and among the young, religion in the media, religious involvement in social services, and interfaith issues and interaction fills important gaps in the knowledge and understanding of Singapore’s religious diversity and complexity. A collective effort of researchers and practitioners, it is a timely and useful reference for scholars, decision-makers, leaders and practitioners as well as for concerned citizens and followers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aReligious pluralism--Singapore--Congresses. 0aReligious tolerance--Singapore--Congresses. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh1 aBuang, Sa’eda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChee, Tham Seong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheong, Pauline Hope, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChew, Phyllis Ghim-Lian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeBernardi, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDetenber, Benjamin H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEng, Kuah-Pearce Khun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEng, Lai Ah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoh, Robbie B. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHameed, Shahiraa Sahul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHui, Anita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIbrahim, Azhar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIbrahim, Nur Amali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaur, Arunajeet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKiong, Tong Chee, econtributor